Update to reflect additional 3 months of measured values.  Revising estimate of probability for 414-416 PPM range downward based primarily on comparison of month-month change trends over the year compared with previous years. After accounting for the average difference between the December whole-month mean value and the mean 1 December value, It appears that in order to remain below 414 PPM, the month-month rate of change between each month over the rest of 2020 would need to average only a little below the average rate of change (~1/7 of a standard deviation) for those months over the last 10 years.  Distinctly possible; over the last ten years, this seems to have happened over the last four months of the year a couple of times, most notably in 2013.  Superficial comparison between large-scale weather patterns of 2020 & 3013 for last few months does not seem to show 2020 “looking like” 2013 going into the last four months of the year, but I say that with low confidence - my understanding of large-scale weather patterns is just not sophisticated enough to see any underlying correspondences that would affect this. As of this writing (almost halfway through August), the Jul-Aug change appears well above the average; it’s possible that this could suggest a rate of change beginning to run above normal, but more likely that it’s just an artifact of where we are in the month and of no real diagnostic value:  CO2 concentration values averaged over the first two weeks of August have consistently been ~.21 PPM higher than the whole-month average values; correcting for that brings the rate of change right back on trend.   Still have several scenarios that “feel right” to me placing the value above 414 PPM, but the assumptions underlying them are not in fact particularly strong.  This probability estimate is especially sensitive to:
- measured values across September and October;
- new (to me) information pointing up substantive similarities/differences between large-scale weather patterns this year and other previous years, particularly 2013 and 2016.

Updating to add a couple observations based on the ESRL data:
- Simple trends give a baseline of the December average breaking 414 PPM in 4/5 scenarios;
- 1 December varies from December whole-month mean by an average of -0.127% (+/- .02); accounting for that brings some scenarios back down below 414 PPM;
- At a quick look, profile of the 2020 numbers to date (based on month-month change) is dead on trend with the last 10 years; for the very little that it’s worth, thus far the 2020 profile resembles those of 2017 and 2013 more strongly than other recent years, and modifying the baseline with assumptions based on those years brings most scenarios back up well above 414 PPM;
- Reaching either the 416 PPM and the 412 PPM levels would require sustained deviations from the average rate of change outside anything that seems likely, something on the order of the month-to-month rate of change running consistently 20-30% outside of normal, and always deviating in the same direction - not impossible certainly, but also not likely - odds run quite a bit less than 1/100;
- In general, this CO2 number does not look very sensitive to short-term human changes.  By my count, keeping the level below 414 PPM on 1 December from where we are now would require downward deviation of ~3-4% from average in the rate CO2 is added to the atmosphere (from all sources, not just human, and assuming that CO2 fixation during N hemisphere summer stays right on average); easily within the realm of natural variation, but a heavy lift indeed for human factors alone;
- Quick look at the general outlook for northern hemisphere summer doesn’t give much reason to think that CO2 fixation will increase, but this is something that could have a dramatic impact on the probabilities;
- One or more of the below would seriously change my estimate of the probabilities: 
    - 1) Weather - N hemisphere (or ocean) having an unexpectedly productive (or poor) growing season; also, if one of the strong Nino/Nina effects comes into play (NOAA estimate is 60% chance of remaining in neutral Nino effect for this year), would have to look at effect of changing Pacific H2O temps on marine CO2 sequestration as well as effect on terrestrial growing season;
    - 2) Major natural CO2 emitting event;
    - 3) Strong deviations from expectation in NOAA CO2 observational data from coming months;
    - 4) Much stronger than expected change in human CO2 emissions because of... whatever might cause something this big (back of the envelope math suggests that absent significant movement in the natural factors, this would have to be REAL serious - something on the order of a 60% reduction).
